  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "As soon as this was announced to Abimelech, he went with all his men to Mount Zalmon, took hatchets in his hand, cut down branches from the trees, and laid them upon his shoulders, and commanded his people to do the same. These branches they laid upon the hold, and set the hold on fire over them (the inhabitants of the tower who had taken refuge there), so that all the people of the tower of Shechem (about one thousand persons) perished, both men and women. Mount Zalmon, which is mentioned again in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 68:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", was a dark, thickly-wooded mountain near Shechem, - a kind of \"Black Forest,\" as Luther has rendered the name. The plural kardumoth, \"axes,\" may be explained on the ground that Abimelech took axes not only for himself but for his people also. מה in a relative sense, as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 23:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (see Ewald, 331, b.). ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]